<font color="#FF0000">A MODEST TRIBUTE ON THIS DAY</font><br>
<tt>Wed Apr 30  2:30:41 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
A while back I needed back surgery and it was arranged for me to fly to Oahu to have the procedure done at a hospital there. I landed at Honolulu airport and arranged for a cab to drive me to the hospital. I got in the back seat and while the elderly driver took off, I noticed on the identification plaque his picture and a Vietnamese name. It was Nguyen Hiep. Although Hawaii has a large Vietnamese population, I have met no more than the fingers on my hand as I had left Oahu years before the influx of refugees and by the time they spilled over to the outer Islands, I had squirreled my family in isolation in the mountains. I had a desire to talk with some in the community, but because of logistics, it never happened.<br><br>
I decided that I would try to break the ice with this guy, so I asked him if he was from Vietnam. Dumb question, I thought to myself, but was at a loss as to what else to say. His English was very rough, but, he confirmed that he was and, encouraged that he didn't tell me to flake off, I informed him that I was a veteran and that I was in Vietnam for a couple of years. It was evident that both of us were uncomfortable, a silence grew after he acknowledge what I told him, so I decided to let him off the hook, sat back in my seat and remained silent. We hit some rough after work traffic, and the cab continued at a slow pace. He kept glancing in his rear view mirror at me and I pretended not to notice and stared at his picture on the placard. He asked me a question which was followed by another, and another. Just minor chit-chat, where did I live, what was I going to the hospital for, etc.. I came back with, when did he leave 'Nam and he told me, &quot;a long time ago.&quot; He tried to be vague, but, being as considerate as I could, I was able to extract his history, bit by bit.<br><br>
Mr. Nguyen was an ARVN ranger. He was a career NCO and had served many years in the service. When the South fell to the communists, he was married with two young boys. He was placed in a re-education camp where he stayed for two years. He was finally able to escape, get his wife and kids and headed for the interior and finally crossing into Cambodia. It took them months to walk north through Cambodia as the Khmer Rouge was very active and in control of the countryside. More than once, he and his family came close to capture. Though he was extremely vague at a point of his exodus, I was able to discern that this was where he had lost his wife and one of his sons. How, he would not say, and I would not ask. To this day I think of that travel he took as the Vietnamese Trail of Tears, as I suspect he was not the only one to have taken this route. They suffered long bouts of hunger and illnesses.<br><br>
When they had reached Thailand, he and his son were placed in a refugee camp, where they stayed until 1980 when they were allowed to enter the US. With help, he was able to get a job as a cab driver to support himself and his son. At the time I met him, his son was starting at the University of Hawaii, Manoa Campus.<br><br>
By the time we reached the hospital, I was in a cold sweat. My heart was pounding and I felt I would jump out of my skin should any said &quot;Boo&quot;. I was totally mesmerized by his story and felt myself in the bush with him and his family and the fears and threats they endured. It was a couple minutes before I realized that we had stopped. I handed him the fare plus tip and got out. I had no baggage, nothing in the trunk, but he got out anyway and walked slowly around the car where I stood. For the first time, I saw his entire face, cragged with deep fissures and dark complexion. His eyes seemed dull and tired. He stood and just looked at me. I wanted to say something, something profound, but I was at a loss for words. I reached into my pocket and grabbed all the money I had. I gave it to him and told him to buy something for his son for me. After trying to give it back, he relented. He gave me a slight hug and got back in the cab and drove off.<br><br>
I went into the hospital, checked in and I was prepped for surgery. The last thing I thought of before being put under, was Nguyen Hiep. The first thing I thought of upon waking was Nguyen Hiep. I spent three days in the hospital, and much of what I thought of was Nguyen Hiep. When a cab was called for me to go to the airport, I had hoped to see him one last time, but it was not to be.<br><br>
When I arrived back home, I could not shake him or his adventures from my mind. Two weeks, and many phone calls later, I found out the cab company he worked for and their mailing address. I wrote a letter, but remembering that his difficulty speaking and reading English hampered his citizenship process, I found someone to translate it into Vietnamese. In the letter, I offered to send him a large South Vietnamese flag that I had brought home from 'Nam with me. I packaged the flag, addressed the letter, but I never was able to bring myself to mail either one. To this day, they sit on my desk to constantly remind me of him and his family.<br><br>
*************************************************<br><br>
&quot;a friend of mine from middle school escaped by boat in the early &quot;80's, but remember when Thai pirates boarded the boat and cut off her father's ears and killed him as she watched. And she told this story without crying, without any kind of waver to her voice, and I felt so in awe, even though we were two twelve year olds sitting in her room listening to the &quot;dirty dancing&quot; soundtrack, of all things, that she could relate this kind of tragedy with this totally mature depth.&quot;   by Anon - a Vietnamese-American woman<br><br>
These stories are true. The sad part is that I don't have to make them up. They are out there, thousands, no, tens of thousands of stories very similar in nature. All you have to do is listen, just listen.
